{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 01:07:41.116184", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope and objective\\n- Detect anomalies\\n- Localize faulty device(s)\\n- Identify the root cause based on evidence from the running network\\n\\nSummary of current network health\\n- IP reachability: Healthy. Broad reachability tests across many subnets show 0% loss and low RTTs. Hosts can reach the server farm subnet (10.200.0.0/24) by IP.\\n- Routing/OSPF: Healthy. All FRR routers show OSPF adjacencies in Full state with expected neighbors. OSPF tables on core, distribution, and server-access routers contain correct routes for access subnets and 10.200.0.0/24.\\n- DHCP: Healthy. Access hosts have valid dynamically assigned addresses and default gateways, indicating relay/lease operation works.\\n- HTTP services: Listening and reachable by IP. The load balancer and all web servers have TCP 80 listening, and HTTP GETs by IP to 10.200.0.7 (LB) succeed with reasonable response times.\\n\\nPrimary anomaly detected\\n- DNS is down for the enterprise zone.\\n  - Symptom: Hosts cannot resolve local FQDNs (e.g., web99.local, web0.local…web3.local).\\n  - Evidence:\\n    - Host resolv.conf points to nameserver 10.200.0.2 (the DNS server) on both access hosts.\\n    - getent hosts for web99.local and the web servers returns no records; nslookup to 10.200.0.2 returns “connection refused”.\\n    - On dns_server (10.200.0.2), no DNS service is listening on UDP/TCP 53 (netstat shows only 127.0.0.11 ephemeral services).\\n    - Systemd: named (BIND) is loaded but inactive (dead); bind9 service is also inactive (dead).\\n    - Network connectivity to the DNS server by IP is fine (ICMP replies, no packet loss), ruling out routing/connectivity problems.\\n  - Impact: Name resolution across the enterprise to local services fails. Users can only reach services by IP; any workflows relying on FQDNs are broken (including accessing web99.local).\\n\\nAdditional observations\\n- HTTP load balancer and web servers:\\n  - load_balancer has eth0 in 10.200.0.0/24 (service-facing) and eth1 in 20.200.0.0/24 (backend-facing). The 20.200.0.0/24 backend is not in OSPF tables observed on server_access_router, indicating it is isolated from hosts, as designed. This aligns with the requirement that backend servers are not directly reachable from hosts.\\n  - Curl tests to 10.200.0.7 (LB) by IP are successful (total ~1.03 s), confirming application-layer availability via IP.\\n- Minor note: Some curl_web_test outputs to FQDNs show namelookup:0.000000 with very short totals; however, authoritative tests (getent/nslookup) confirm DNS resolution failures. The curl output should not be considered authoritative for resolution status here.\\n\\nLocalization\\n- Faulty device: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\\n- All network paths to the DNS server are operational; the failure is local to the DNS service on that host.\\n\\nRoot cause\\n- The DNS service (BIND/named) on dns_server is not running or not bound to port 53.\\n  - Confirmed by:\\n    - systemctl showing named and bind9 both inactive (dead).\\n    - No :53 listener present on dns_server.\\n    - Client-side “connection refused” to 10.200.0.2:53, while ICMP and routing are healthy.\\n\\nNon-issues ruled out\\n- OSPF adjacencies and routing propagation: Working as designed (Full neighbors, correct OSPF routes present).\\n- Access switching/Layer 2 connectivity: Hosts have established links and obtained DHCP leases; pings across areas are clean.\\n- HTTP services and load-balancer reachability by IP: Functional.\\n- Isolation of backend network: Present via 20.200.0.0/24 and not advertised, which matches the design intent.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network forwarding plane and OSPF control plane are healthy.\\n- The enterprise-wide service degradation is due to a DNS application-layer failure on dns_server (10.200.0.2). The DNS daemon is not running/listening, causing connection refused on port 53 and breaking hostname resolution for all local services (e.g., web99.local and webN.local)., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='8ac1f0e9-a2ce-46cb-a65b-9146b8a40b3c'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
